data.content:
Here are the modern MSTest replacements for each assertion:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    var admin = Assert.ContainsSingle(users.Where(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);
}
```

**What changed and why:**

| Original | Replacement | Benefit |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Failure says "expected non-empty" instead of "expected True, got False" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Failure shows actual count |
| `users.Single()` + null check | `Assert.ContainsSingle()` | Combines "exactly one match" into one assertion and returns the element |

`Assert.IsTrue(users.All(...))` has no built-in replacement — it's fine to keep as-is since there's no specialized "all match predicate" assertion in MSTest. The `Assert.IsNotNull(admin)` on the last line is technically redundant after `ContainsSingle` (which throws if no match), but you can keep it for clarity.
